		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />You're forgetting that 6502 is built to be simple and isn't x86 assembly. You should go through the first few Nerdy Nights tutorials and learn how the 6502 works and you'll see it's really, really simple. I know it requires a certain way of thinking that is rare for even other programmers, but still when you can think that way, it becomes really straightforward and simple. IMO, if you'll take the dive and just go through the first 6502 assembly tutorials, even if you learn it you can make a more educated decision of what is right for you. Just saying you don't wanna learn and use 6502 because x86 is total garbage isn't that good of an ide, heh. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" />

		

